Certainly! Here is a complete, working Rust implementation of **Batcher's Odd-Even Mergesort** for sorting slices of any type that implements `Ord + Copy`.

This implementation works in-place, like most in-memory sorting routines. For educational clarity, this is a recursive, not heavily optimized, version.

```rust
fn compare_and_swap<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T], i: usize, j: usize) {
    if arr[i] > arr[j] {
        arr.swap(i, j);
    }
}

// Perform the odd-even merge for the subarray arr[offset..offset+cnt]
fn odd_even_merge<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T], offset: usize, cnt: usize, r: usize) {
    if cnt > 1 {
        let m = r * 2;
        if m < cnt {
            odd_even_merge(arr, offset, cnt, m);
            odd_even_merge(arr, offset + r, cnt, m);

            for i in (offset + r..offset + cnt - r).step_by(m) {
                compare_and_swap(arr, i, i + r);
            }
        } else {
            compare_and_swap(arr, offset, offset + r);
        }
    }
}

// The main recursive function: sorts arr[offset..offset+cnt]
fn odd_even_mergesort_recurse<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T], offset: usize, cnt: usize) {
    if cnt > 1 {
        let mid = cnt / 2;
        odd_even_mergesort_recurse(arr, offset, mid);
        odd_even_mergesort_recurse(arr, offset + mid, cnt - mid);
        odd_even_merge(arr, offset, cnt, 1);
    }
}

// Public interface. Will log panic if arr.len() is not a power of 2.
pub fn odd_even_mergesort<T: Ord>(arr: &mut [T]) {
    let n = arr.len();
    // Batcher's (and most comparison network) sorts require size == power of 2.
    assert!(n.is_power_of_two(), "Length must be a power of 2");
    odd_even_mergesort_recurse(arr, 0, n);
}

// Example usage and test
fn main() {
    let mut arr = [5, 2, 9, 1, 5, 6, 3, 7];
    odd_even_mergesort(&mut arr);
    println!("{:?}", arr);

    // For verification:
    let mut arr2 = [9, 8, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2];
    odd_even_mergesort(&mut arr2);
    assert_eq!(arr2, [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9]);
}
```

## Notes

- **Power-of-two size**: Batcher's mergesort network is designed for `N` that is a power of two. The public function asserts this.
- **Generic type**: You may add bounds (e.g., `Copy`) as needed if your use-case requires.
- If you wish to sort arbitrary-length slices, you can pad the input with sentinels and then remove them after sorting (or, alternatively, adapt the algorithm).
- This code is recursive and not optimized for performance, but it is clear and faithful to the classic Batcher odd-even merge.

## References

- [Batcher's original paper (PDF)](https://www.cs.rutgers.edu/~venugopa/parallel_summer2011/Batcher.pdf)
- [Wikipedia: Bitonic Sorter](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitonic_sorter) (closely related sorting network)
- [Sorting Networks: Theory & Practice](https://sorting-network.netlify.app/)

