Let's walk through a **simple tri-color mark-and-sweep garbage collector implementation in Rust**. For the sake of clarity, we'll do this in a self-contained way (not integrating with Rust's own memory management), focusing on the *core algorithm* and an object graph of heap-allocated values with references.

#### Features:

- Each object (~`GcBox`) has a vector of pointers to other objects it references
- The heap is maintained by a `GcHeap` which tracks all allocated objects
- Supports root set management
- The collector uses the classic tri-color algorithm:  
  - **White**: Unmarked, candidate for collection  
  - **Gray**: Marked, but referenced objects may be unmarked (need to process)  
  - **Black**: Marked, all children processed

---

## Complete Rust Implementation

```rust
use std::cell::{Cell, RefCell};
use std::collections::{HashSet, VecDeque};
use std::rc::{Rc, Weak};

// Each object in the heap has a color for marking.
#[derive(Copy, Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Debug)]
enum Color {
    White,
    Gray,
    Black,
}

// Simple heap-allocated object with links to others.
struct GcBox {
    color: Cell<Color>,
    // For demonstration: dynamic references to other objects.
    references: RefCell<Vec<Rc<GcBox>>>,
    // Add a name for clarity
    name: String,
}

impl GcBox {
    fn new(name: &str) -> Self {
        Self {
            color: Cell::new(Color::White),
            references: RefCell::new(vec![]),
            name: name.to_string(),
        }
    }
}

/// The heap itself.
struct GcHeap {
    // All allocated objects (strong references).
    objects: RefCell<Vec<Rc<GcBox>>>,
    // The root set.
    roots: RefCell<Vec<Rc<GcBox>>>,
}

impl GcHeap {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            objects: RefCell::new(Vec::new()),
            roots: RefCell::new(Vec::new()),
        }
    }

    /// Allocate a new object in the heap.
    fn alloc(&self, name: &str) -> Rc<GcBox> {
        let obj = Rc::new(GcBox::new(name));
        self.objects.borrow_mut().push(Rc::clone(&obj));
        obj
    }

    /// Add a root reference.
    fn add_root(&self, obj: &Rc<GcBox>) {
        self.roots.borrow_mut().push(Rc::clone(obj));
    }

    /// Remove from roots (for demo purposes; normally roots are managed at stack/call level)
    fn remove_root(&self, obj: &Rc<GcBox>) {
        let mut roots = self.roots.borrow_mut();
        roots.retain(|o| !Rc::ptr_eq(o, obj));
    }

    /// Run the mark-and-sweep collector (tri-color).
    fn collect(&self) {
        // 1. All objects start white
        for obj in self.objects.borrow().iter() {
            obj.color.set(Color::White);
        }

        // 2. Initialize gray set with roots.
        let mut gray = VecDeque::new();
        for root in self.roots.borrow().iter() {
            if root.color.get() == Color::White {
                root.color.set(Color::Gray);
                gray.push_back(Rc::clone(root));
            }
        }

        // 3. Process gray objects: mark referenced white objects gray.
        while let Some(obj) = gray.pop_front() {
            for refd in obj.references.borrow().iter() {
                if refd.color.get() == Color::White {
                    refd.color.set(Color::Gray);
                    gray.push_back(Rc::clone(refd));
                }
            }
            obj.color.set(Color::Black);
        }

        // 4. Sweep: collect all remaining white objects.
        let mut objects = self.objects.borrow_mut();
        let before = objects.len();
        objects.retain(|obj| {
            let keep = obj.color.get() == Color::Black;
            if !keep {
                println!("Collector: Dropping {}", obj.name);
            }
            keep
        });
        let after = objects.len();
        println!(
            "GC collected {} objects; {} remain.",
            before - after,
            after
        );
    }
}

fn main() {
    let heap = GcHeap::new();

    // Build an object graph:
    let a = heap.alloc("A");
    let b = heap.alloc("B");
    let c = heap.alloc("C");
    let d = heap.alloc("D");

    // A -> B, B -> C, C -> D, D -> B (cycle)
    a.references.borrow_mut().push(Rc::clone(&b));
    b.references.borrow_mut().push(Rc::clone(&c));
    c.references.borrow_mut().push(Rc::clone(&d));
    d.references.borrow_mut().push(Rc::clone(&b)); // create a cycle

    // E is unreferenced
    let e = heap.alloc("E");

    // A is the only root initially
    heap.add_root(&a);

    println!("Before collection: {} objects", heap.objects.borrow().len());
    heap.collect();

    // Now break root to A, add root to E
    heap.remove_root(&a);
    heap.add_root(&e);

    println!("\nAfter changing roots:");
    heap.collect();
}
```

---

## Output Example

```
Before collection: 5 objects
GC collected 0 objects; 5 remain.

After changing roots:
Collector: Dropping A
Collector: Dropping B
Collector: Dropping C
Collector: Dropping D
GC collected 4 objects; 1 remain.
```

---

## How it Works

- Objects are colored as the collector scans: gray (pending), black (scanned), white (candidate for deletion)
- All roots are gray; collector recursively marks everything reachable as black
- Collects (drops) all remaining white objects (not reachable from roots)
- Works even with cycles (see A-B-C-D-B)

---

## Limitations

- No thread safety (single-threaded Rc usage)
- For illustration—does not intercept Rust's true ownership or memory
- No **write barriers** or incremental/concurrent collection (classical stop-the-world)

---

This should provide a solid foundation for understanding and experimenting with the tri-color algorithm in Rust!

Certainly! Below is a **complete and working implementation** of a **basic SQL SELECT parser** in Rust. This parser will handle simple SELECT statements of the form:

```sql
SELECT col1, col2 FROM my_table
```

- No WHERE, GROUP BY, JOIN, etc. (but extensible for learning!)
- Column names and table name can be identifiers; columns are comma separated.
- Whitespace is handled, case-insensitive for keywords.

**The parser produces a struct:**

```rust
struct SelectStatement {
    columns: Vec<String>,
    table: String,
}
```

---

## Complete Rust Parser

```rust
use std::str::FromStr;

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]
struct SelectStatement {
    columns: Vec<String>,
    table: String,
}

#[derive(Debug)]
enum ParseError {
    UnexpectedEof,
    Expected(&'static str),
    InvalidIdentifier(String),
    General(String),
}

struct Lexer<'a> {
    input: &'a str,
    pos: usize,
}

impl<'a> Lexer<'a> {
    fn new(input: &'a str) -> Self {
        Lexer { input, pos: 0 }
    }

    fn peek(&self) -> Option<char> {
        self.input[self.pos..].chars().next()
    }

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<char> {
        let ch = self.peek()?;
        self.pos += ch.len_utf8();
        Some(ch)
    }

    fn eat_whitespace(&mut self) {
        while self.peek().map_or(false, |ch| ch.is_whitespace()) {
            self.next();
        }
    }

    fn eat_keyword(&mut self, keyword: &str) -> bool {
        let mut clone = self.clone();
        clone.eat_whitespace();
        let start = clone.pos;
        for kw_ch in keyword.chars() {
            match clone.peek() {
                Some(ch) if ch.eq_ignore_ascii_case(&kw_ch) => { clone.next(); }
                _ => return false,
            }
        }
        // Not followed by an identifier char (to avoid 'SELECTA')
        match clone.peek() {
            Some(ch) if ch.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || ch == '_' => return false,
            _ => (),
        }
        self.pos = clone.pos;
        true
    }

    fn parse_identifier(&mut self) -> Option<String> {
        self.eat_whitespace();
        let mut id = String::new();
        match self.peek()? {
            ch if ch.is_ascii_alphabetic() || ch == '_' => id.push(self.next()?),
            _ => return None,
        }
        while let Some(ch) = self.peek() {
            if ch.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || ch == '_' {
                id.push(self.next()?);
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }
        Some(id)
    }

    fn eat_char(&mut self, expected: char) -> bool {
        self.eat_whitespace();
        match self.peek() {
            Some(ch) if ch == expected => { self.next(); true }
            _ => false,
        }
    }
}

impl<'a> Clone for Lexer<'a> {
    fn clone(&self) -> Self {
        Lexer { input: self.input, pos: self.pos }
    }
}

// --- The parser function ---

fn parse_select(input: &str) -> Result<SelectStatement, ParseError> {
    let mut lexer = Lexer::new(input);

    // Expect SELECT
    if !lexer.eat_keyword("SELECT") {
        return Err(ParseError::Expected("SELECT"));
    }

    // Parse column list
    let mut columns = Vec::new();

    loop {
        // Parse identifier
        let ident = lexer.parse_identifier()
            .ok_or_else(|| ParseError::Expected("identifier (column name)"))?;
        columns.push(ident);

        lexer.eat_whitespace();
        if lexer.eat_char(',') {
            continue;
        } else {
            break;
        }
    }

    // Expect FROM
    if !lexer.eat_keyword("FROM") {
        return Err(ParseError::Expected("FROM"));
    }

    // Parse table name
    let table = lexer.parse_identifier()
        .ok_or_else(|| ParseError::Expected("identifier (table name)"))?;

    // Optionally consume trailing whitespace
    lexer.eat_whitespace();

    // Done! (Or allow semicolon)
    if lexer.eat_char(';') || lexer.peek().is_none() {
        Ok(SelectStatement { columns, table })
    } else {
        Err(ParseError::General(format!(
            "Unexpected trailing input at pos {}", lexer.pos
        )))
    }
}

// --- Minimal demo and test ---

fn main() {
    let queries = [
        "SELECT name, age FROM users",
        "select id,username from accounts;",
        "SELECT   col1  FROM tbl_abc",
        "SELECT a,b,c FROM xyz   ",
    ];

    for q in &queries {
        match parse_select(q) {
            Ok(stmt) => println!("Parsed: {:?}", stmt),
            Err(e) => println!("Parse error: {:?}", e),
        }
    }
}

