Certainly! Below is a minimal yet **working tri-color marking garbage collector implemented in Rust**. This implementation is **educational**—to keep it simple, it works in a single-threaded/arena context, not multithreaded, and doesn’t hook into the Rust heap or destructors. Instead, we simulate "heap objects" managed inside the GC. The example uses `Rc<RefCell<T>>` to allow mutable graph traversal and store object references. Root objects are maintained in a root set.

## Implementation

```rust
use std::{
    cell::{Cell, RefCell},
    collections::VecDeque,
    rc::{Rc, Weak},
};

/// The color of a GC object.
#[derive(Copy, Clone, PartialEq, Eq, Debug)]
enum Color {
    White,
    Grey,
    Black,
}

/// A GC-managed object holding references to other objects.
struct GcObj {
    color: Cell<Color>,
    children: RefCell<Vec<Gc>>,
    value: i32, // for demonstration
}

/// This is a wrapper for an Rc to GcObj.
#[derive(Clone)]
struct Gc(Rc<GcObj>);

impl GcObj {
    fn new(value: i32) -> Gc {
        Gc(Rc::new(GcObj {
            color: Cell::new(Color::White),
            children: RefCell::new(Vec::new()),
            value,
        }))
    }

    /// Add a child (outgoing edge).
    fn add_child(&self, child: &Gc) {
        self.children.borrow_mut().push(child.clone());
    }
}

struct GarbageCollector {
    // The heap simply owns all objects created
    heap: RefCell<Vec<Gc>>,
    // The set of root objects
    roots: RefCell<Vec<Gc>>,
}

impl GarbageCollector {
    fn new() -> GarbageCollector {
        GarbageCollector {
            heap: RefCell::new(Vec::new()),
            roots: RefCell::new(Vec::new()),
        }
    }

    /// Allocate a new object managed by the GC.
    fn alloc(&self, value: i32) -> Gc {
        let obj = GcObj::new(value);
        self.heap.borrow_mut().push(obj.clone());
        obj
    }

    /// Set the roots (for this demo, overwrite).
    fn set_roots(&self, roots: Vec<Gc>) {
        self.roots.replace(roots);
    }

    /// The tri-color mark-and-sweep algorithm.
    fn collect(&self) {
        // Step 1: Paint all objects white
        for obj in self.heap.borrow().iter() {
            obj.0.color.set(Color::White);
        }

        // Step 2: Initialize greys with roots
        let mut grey: VecDeque<Gc> = VecDeque::new();

        for root in self.roots.borrow().iter() {
            root.0.color.set(Color::Grey);
            grey.push_back(root.clone());
        }

        // Step 3: Mark phase
        while let Some(obj) = grey.pop_front() {
            for child in obj.0.children.borrow().iter() {
                if child.0.color.get() == Color::White {
                    child.0.color.set(Color::Grey);
                    grey.push_back(child.clone());
                }
            }
            obj.0.color.set(Color::Black);
        }

        // Step 4: Sweep phase
        // Remove all white objects (unreachable)
        let mut heap = self.heap.borrow_mut();
        let mut survivors = Vec::new();

        for obj in heap.drain(..) {
            if obj.0.color.get() == Color::Black {
                survivors.push(obj);
            } // else: GC'd (drop here)
        }

        *heap = survivors;
    }
}

// Demo usage:
fn main() {
    let gc = GarbageCollector::new();

    // Allocate objects
    let a = gc.alloc(1);
    let b = gc.alloc(2);
    let c = gc.alloc(3);
    let d = gc.alloc(4);

    // Setup object graph:
    // a -> b
    // b -> c
    // c -> a (cycle)
    // d (unconnected)
    a.0.add_child(&b);
    b.0.add_child(&c);
    c.0.add_child(&a);

    // Set roots to [a]
    gc.set_roots(vec![a.clone()]);

    println!("Before GC: heap has {} objects", gc.heap.borrow().len());

    gc.collect();

    println!("After GC: heap has {} objects", gc.heap.borrow().len());

    for (ix, obj) in gc.heap.borrow().iter().enumerate() {
        println!(
            "Object {}: value={}, color={:?}",
            ix,
            obj.0.value,
            obj.0.color.get()
        );
    }

    // Now a, b, c remain. d is collected.

    // If we remove a from roots, all will be collected:
    gc.set_roots(vec![]);
    gc.collect();

    println!("After removing roots, heap has {} objects", gc.heap.borrow().len());
}

```

## Features

- **Tri-color marking:** Objects are colored white, grey, or black during collection.
- **Sweeping:** Unreachable (white) objects are dropped from the heap.
- **Handles cycles:** It can collect cyclic garbage (since no reliance on reference counts).
- **Simple graph-building API:** Add references between objects.
- **Manual root management.**

## Output Example

```
Before GC: heap has 4 objects
After GC: heap has 3 objects
Object 0: value=1, color=Black
Object 1: value=2, color=Black
Object 2: value=3, color=Black
After removing roots, heap has 0 objects
```

